Signal Architecture

The system is a dual-layer filter. Both layers must agree simultaneously for a signal to fire. This dual
confirmation is the core reason the signal has low frequency and high precision.

L A Y E R 1 — M A R K E T S T A T E T R A N S I T I O N D E T E C T O R
Each price bar’s return is scaled and reduced to a residue state using a modular mapping derived from
the I Ching’s trigram system. The I Ching provides a mathematically complete framework for encoding
momentum states — this mapping is exact, not approximate. Specific transition sequences between
these states are identified as expansion signals — moments where a compressed or receptive system
breaks into active outward movement. The signal candidate is generated whenever one of these
transitions occurs. The specific transitions are proprietary and not disclosed in this document.
Four specific trigram transitions are identified as expansion signals — moments described in the I Ching
as a compressed or receptive system breaking into active outward movement. A signal candidate is
generated whenever one of these four transitions occurs in consecutive bars.
The four transitions and their I Ching interpretations are part of the proprietary framework and are not
disclosed in this document.

L A Y E R 2 — P R O P R I E T A R Y G R I D S T A T E F I L T E R
The same scaled return is simultaneously mapped onto a proprietary 36-position matrix — a 6x6 grid of
numbers with an independent mathematical origin, received before any trading application was known.
The matrix defines compression zones and release zones within the market’s current state. The Layer 1
signal is only accepted when the market’s current state falls within the grid’s compression zone. The
specific qualifying states vary by asset and are part of the core IP — they are not disclosed here.
